In [8]:
# From above observation we can conclude that price column does contains outlier.
In [9]:
# I created a list of values from the "make" column 
# that have outliers in relation to the "price" column.

outlier = ['dodge','toyota','plymouth','mitsubishi','isuzu','honda']
In [10]:
# I wrote a function that takes a dataframe and a column name as parameters, 
# removes outliers in the specified column, 
# and returns the updated dataframe with no outliers.
def remove_outlier(df_in, col_name):
    q1 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df_in[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1 #Interquartile range
    fence_low  = q1-1.5*iqr
    fence_high = q3+1.5*iqr
    df_out = df_in.loc[(df_in[col_name] > fence_low) & (df_in[col_name] < fence_high)]
    return df_out
In [11]:
# I created an empty dataframe and used a for loop to iterate over the 
# "outlier" variable (contains "make" with outliers with respect to the 'price' column)

# I utilized the "remove_outlier" function which takes two parameters:

# 1) df_in: the dataframe containing a specified "make" value for each iteration, 
# generating a new dataframe each time.

# 2) col_name: the name of the column from which outliers are to be removed.

# I removed the outliers present in each dataframe using the drop function and combined 
#the cleaned dataframes into a new dataframe named "df2" through concatenation.

df2 = pd.DataFrame()
for i in outlier:
    make = df.loc[df['make'] == i]
    t = remove_outlier(make, 'price')
    df.drop(list(make.index),inplace=True)
    df2 = pd.concat([df2,t])
In [12]:
df = pd.concat([df,df2]).sort_values('make')
